TITLE: Implementing JSON/P for Cross-Domain Requests in JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: This JavaScript function demonstrates the JSON/P (JSON with Padding) technique to bypass the Same-Origin Policy. It dynamically creates an HTML <script> element, sets its 'src' attribute to a cross-domain API endpoint (YouTube Data API in this case), and includes a callback function name ('videoDetailsLoaded') in the URL parameters. Appending this script element to the document's <head> executes the script retrieved from the URL, allowing cross-domain data fetching.
SOURCE: https://github.com/officedev/office-js-docs-pr/blob/main/docs/concepts/privacy-and-security.md#_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: js
CODE:
```
// Dynamically create an HTML SCRIPT element that obtains the details for the specified video.
function loadVideoDetails(videoIndex) {
    // Dynamically create a new HTML SCRIPT element in the webpage.
    const script = document.createElement("script");
    // Specify the URL to retrieve the indicated video from a feed of a current list of videos,
    // as the value of the src attribute of the SCRIPT element. 
    script.setAttribute("src", "https://gdata.youtube.com/feeds/api/videos/" + 
        videos[videoIndex].Id + "?alt=json-in-script&amp;callback=videoDetailsLoaded");
    // Insert the SCRIPT element at the end of the HEAD section.
    document.getElementsByTagName('head')[0].appendChild(script);
}
