TITLE: Applying PivotDateFilter to Excel PivotTable Field using Office JS API
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to apply a `PivotDateFilter` to a specific PivotField ('Date Updated') within an Excel PivotTable named 'Farm Sales'. It first ensures the corresponding hierarchy is part of the PivotTable's row hierarchies. Then, it defines a date filter to include only data on or after '2020-08-01' with month specificity and applies it to the field. The operations are batched using `Excel.run` and synchronized with `context.sync()`.
SOURCE: https://github.com/officedev/office-js-docs-pr/blob/main/docs/excel/excel-add-ins-pivottables.md#_snippet_11

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
```js
await Excel.run(async (context) => {
    // Get the PivotTable and the date hierarchy.
    let pivotTable = context.workbook.worksheets.getActiveWorksheet().pivotTables.getItem("Farm Sales");
    let dateHierarchy = pivotTable.rowHierarchies.getItemOrNullObject("Date Updated");
    await context.sync();

    // PivotFilters can only be applied to PivotHierarchies that are being used for pivoting.
    // If it's not already there, add "Date Updated" to the hierarchies.
    if (dateHierarchy.isNullObject) {
        dateHierarchy = pivotTable.rowHierarchies.add(pivotTable.hierarchies.getItem("Date Updated"));
    }

    // Apply a date filter to filter out anything logged before August.
    let filterField = dateHierarchy.fields.getItem("Date Updated");
    let dateFilter = {
        condition: Excel.DateFilterCondition.afterOrEqualTo,
        comparator: {
        date: "2020-08-01",
        specificity: Excel.FilterDatetimeSpecificity.month
        }
    };
    filterField.applyFilter({ dateFilter: dateFilter });

    await context.sync();
});
```
```

